  <subsection xml:id="subsec1-chap2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Hadamard gate</title>
    <p> 
      Hadamard gate is one of the most popular gates in quantum computing.
      The Hadamard operator on one qubit can be written as
    </p>
    
    <me>
      H =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\bigg(
\Big(\ket{0}+\ket{1}\Big)\bra{0}
+
\Big(\ket{0}-\ket{1}\Big)\bra{1}
\bigg)
=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
\bigg(
\ket{0}\bra{0}+\ket{1}\bra{0}
+
\ket{0}\bra{1}-\ket{1}\bra{1}
\bigg)
    </me>
    
    <p>
      which is the Hadamard gate in Dirac notation. Hadamard operation is a rotation of the Block sphere about y axis by <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>, followed by a rotation about <m>x</m> axis by <m>pi</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Exercise 1 <em>Obtain</em>
      <ul>
        <li><me>H\ket{0}</me></li>
        <li><me>H\ket{1}</me></li>
      </ul> 
    </p>

    
  </subsection>

 
      
  
  
